  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>CHAPTER 1: THE BLADES</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>-----</p>
<font size="+3">Chapter 1: The Blades</font>
<p>-----</p>
<p>	A group of drow sat hunched around a decaying log.  The thick forest of Nektulos let no light shine through, but the group didn’t need any natural light to see.  The ultravision granted to all dark elves allowed them to see perfectly even in pitch blackness. Fire beetles, spiderlings, and grass snakes crawled around the group as they sat talking.</p>
<p>	A young warrior equipped in wolf skins stood with his back to the group, watching the surrounding woods intently.  His claymore lay buried in the thick moss growing around the base of the log, easily within his reach should he need it.  A shadow knight sat cross-legged on top of the log, with the other three of the group.  She wore heavy black armor and held a large black-bladed sword that radiated power.  Next to her was a cleric of Innoruuk, who was equipped in a mixture of leather and chainmail armor.  The last of the group was an enchanter, wearing her gray training robe and meditating quietly.</p>
<p>	“See any halflings yet, Ravell?” The shadow knight asked the warrior on watch.</p>
<p>	“Not yet.” Ravell responded. “I don’t understand how those little midgets managed to gain a foothold in Nektulos anyway.  Our stone guards and dragoons should have made short work of them.”</p>
<p>	“They are elusive little creatures,” The cleric responded. “Besides, the stone guards and dragoons have been busy fighting off the lightskins and their allies.”</p>
<p>	Ravell turned away from the woods to face the group. “Will the humans never learn?  They cannot take down Neriak.  They are far too inferior to even take these woods. Which is why these halflings bother me.  They come from much farther away than the humans, why did they succeed where the humans failed?”</p>
<p>	“That is a good question.” The enchanter responded, opening her eyes.</p>
<p>	“Bah! Malice, Ravell, you worry too much.” The shadow knight snorted, jumping up.  “They got lucky, that’s all.  They’ll prove no match for The Blades!”</p>
<p>	“Lilith, you’re not supposed to use the group name outside of Neriak” The cleric closed his book and shot a glare at the shadow knight. “You’ll get all of us tortured because of your loose tongue.  Nobody is supposed to know about The Blades except us four, Lord N’vitar, and his guards.”</p>
<p>	Lilith turned and scowled back. “There’s nobody around, so don’t worry about it, Navarr.”</p>
<p>	“Sometimes there are enemies that cannot be seen.” Malice remarked.</p>
<p>	Ravell turned back towards the woods and grabbed his claymore. “Enough fighting.  Let’s go kill some halflings.”</p>
<p>	“Finally one of you has a smart idea…” Lilith grabbed her sword and cut a nearby snake in half on impulse.</p>
<p>-----</p>
<p>	The four arrived at a giant wooden bridge without trouble.  Under the bridge piranhas swam in the dark murky water, waiting for anyone to attempt to swim across.  A light rain fell and made ripples in the water.  The dark woods became even harder to see into as a thick fog blanketed Nektulos.  Four guards stood stationed around the bridge, two at either end.</p>
<p>	“Alright, Lord N’vitar said the halflings were seen just past the bridge, out in the woods, so everyone be on your guard.”  Ravell instructed.</p>
<p>	A nearby guard overheard and laughed aloud. “Lord N’vitar huh?  So you brats must be The Blades.  Neriak’s ‘elite’ of untrained youth.  Nice scraggly armor, by the way.”</p>
<p>	“I’m trained enough to slaughter you, Corporal D’bth!” Lilith jumped at the guard, but Ravell and Navarr held her back.</p>
<p>	“Ease up, Lilith. Save it for our real enemy.” Ravell whispered.</p>
<p>	Lilith stopped struggling and made a gesture at the guard who now looked like he was enjoying this even more.  “I’ll have my brother slide a dagger between his ribs tonight…” She murmured.</p>
<p>	The group moved on into the foggy woods, keeping close together.  Every tree was covered in thick moss, and it was hard to distinguish one from another.  The rain continued to pour down relentlessly.  Suddenly a light flickered in the distance, but just as quickly it was gone.  Ravell signaled the group to a stop.</p>
<p>	“I think I just saw something cast a spell, but it’s hard to tell in this fog.”</p>
<p>	Lilith grinned. “Then let’s go investigate. Which way?”</p>
<p>	Ravell led them onwards and the group soon found themselves staring at a group of six halflings gathered around a pillar.  Five stood in a semi-circle off of the pillar, and one stood on it casting various spells on the group.</p>
<p>	“So, that’s what a halfling looks like…” Ravell mused.</p>
<p>	“Now imagine them all missing body parts, disemboweled, and lifeless.” Lilith smirked.</p>
<p>	“Alright, here’s the plan,” Ravell began. “Lilith, you and I need to take down that caster first.  Navarr you stand back and keep Lilith and I alive.  Malice, make the rest of the group a little more friendly towards us while we deal with that caster.”</p>
<p>	“Fine then, on your signal.” Lilith donned her black metallic helmet and waited.</p>
<p>	“Blades… CHARGE!” Ravell shouted.</p>
<p>	The halflings heard the shout but couldn’t see their enemies in the fog until they were almost on top of them.  A knight in jet-black armor charged towards the pillar alongside a fighter in wolf-skins.  They instinctively formed a barrier between the druid on the pillar and the charging enemies.</p>
<p>	Ravell jumped clear over the halfling line and continued towards the caster.  Lilith’s armor was far too heavy for her to just jump, so instead she booted her way through the line.  The caster had just finished casting a stoneskin spell as Ravell reached him.  Lilith cleaved at the druid, but it quickly moved out of the way of her blade and began to cast another spell. Ravell chopped downward at the thing’s head, but his blade only scratched the little halfling.  It finished its spell and suddenly Ravell was struck by a ball of fire.  The flames died almost as quickly as they appeared, but there was still enough power in that spell to singe Ravell’s armor and leave him stunned.  Lilith had left the biggest impression on the five other halflings, and as such they were all attacking her.  She didn’t even regard them, as her heavy armor deflected just about every attack thrown her way.  Malice was working her magic, Lilith noticed.  Three of the halflings were now staring blankly into nothing, just standing there.  Lilith laughed and concentrated on the druid.</p>
<p>	Ravell recovered and sheathed his claymore.  Then he pulled out a large axe and a shield and began going after the druid, who was now in the middle of casting another spell.  Ravell slammed his shield into the thing’s head, and the spell fizzled into the air.  Cursing, the halfling attacked Ravell with its wooden stave.  Ravell deflected the attacks as best he could with his shield while making mark after mark on the halfling’s stone skin.  Lilith went up behind the druid and placed her hands on it.  A magenta light appeared around Lilith’s hands and soon enveloped the little halfling.  A sound like a rock shattering came from the halfling, which fell over on its face, quite dead.  Four other halflings stood near the pillar, staring into nothing.  Ravell quickly looked around for the fifth, but didn’t see it anywhere.  Then he realized something that made his stomach rise; Malice and Navarr were gone.</p>
<p>	Lilith went up to the first halfling and raised her sword.  The halfling never even got a chance to fight back before it joined its friend in the afterlife.  Ravell tucked away his shield and axe and grabbed his claymore again.  He took aim for the closest halfling’s head…and lopped it off.</p>
<p>	That’s when Malice appeared again, with five more halflings chasing her.  Navarr appeared off to the side, desperately trying to heal the fleeing enchantress.  Lilith stood frozen in place, the other two halfings dead at her feet.  A look of frustration and fear crossed her usually cocky grin before she turned to Ravell.</p>
<p>	“Well, then. Let’s show this new group what happens when you attack one of The Blades, eh?” She smiled.</p>
<p>	Ravell wore a grim face. “Indeed.” Was all he said.</p>
<p>	The enchantress ran behind Ravell and Lilith and stopped.  Navarr circled around to their backs and stood ready.</p>
<p>	“I’m sorry, my spell broke and I couldn’t get another one off in time to stop that other halfling.  He ran to another group and warned them.  I tried to stop them, but there were too many for me to enchant alone.” Malice explained.</p>
<p>	“Out of the frying pan, into the fire.” Navarr added. “I think this might be it.”</p>
<p>	The halflings were now within a few yards of the group.  Lilith and Ravell charged them, Lilith wearing her cocky grin again, Ravell with a set look of determination.  The halflings were on their guard this time, however, and deflected the charging elves’ attacks and soon had the two drow fighters on the defensive.  Ravell took a short sword in his side, and grimaced.  A stave struck him on the jaw, and a cracking sound announced that it had been broken.  Lilith had been knocked to the ground, her sword tossed aside, and three of the halflings sat there attacking her. Navarr desperately tried to heal the group, but couldn’t keep up with the damage the halflings were doing.  Ravell’s vision blurred red, and he lost himself.  He roared a purely animal roar, and grabbed the halfling wielding the short sword by the head.  Ravell wasn’t weak by any means, in fact he was stronger than any other elf he had ever met.  The surge of adrenaline boosted his strength even more, and he crushed the halfling’s head between his hands.  The halfling holding the stave went down next.  Ravell cleaved him into two separate halves at the midsection with his claymore.  The three halflings attacking Lilith had beaten her unconscious, and turned to see a battered, bloody warrior covered in halfling parts running at them.  The highest-ranking halfling stood his ground, convinced that no elf could fight in that condition for long.  He shouted and rallied the other two into a defensive position.  Ravell fell right into the trap.  He stabbed through one halfling’s head when a stave hit him across the back of his neck.  Then everything went black.</p>
<p>-----</p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Ravell</b> Submited on 5/19/2001</small></td>
